passages.text: F2Q25 Earnings Review: Better-than- feared 2Q update; Gap and Old Navy brands remain strong, but Athleta weaker

GAP reported a modest 2Q beat and reiterated its FY25 sales guidance. Gap and Old Navy drove healthy results in the quarter, both delivering positive comps \((+4\%\) and \(+2\%\) , respectively; though we note each brand decelerated vs. slightly vs. 1Q), while Banana Republic saw sequential acceleration to a \(+4\%\) comp (vs. flat in 1Q). Management also noted sequential improvement in the 2H of the quarter, with July accelerating and trends continuing into August as a result of strong engagement with fall product in the back- to- school season. Offsetting this, Athleta decelerated (comps \(- 9\%\) Y/Y despite easier compares) and drove a surprising gross margin miss for the consolidated entity (2Q GPM - 130bps vs. FactSet consensus - 60bps). This GPM miss was offset by solid SG&A cost control, although this was also driven by a timing shift.

Looking ahead, management's revised FY25 guidance now includes the impact of tariffs, including trade policies in place as of August 7th (and a \(50\%\) tariff rate on India imports, although this is a small sourcing country for GAP). Management now expects a \(\) 150-\ \(175mn net headwind from tariffs (vs. the\) \ \(100 -\) 150mn headwind estimated in May under prior trade policy). Importantly, GAP noted that they do not expect further tariff- driven operating income declines next year due to tariff mitigation, with full mitigation expected over time.

We see several puts and takes in the quarter, but step away from the quarter with our constructive view largely unchanged. We were pleased to see going momentum in GAP's core brands, where strategic initiatives including category expansion and fresh marketing continue to drive healthy growth. Further, management's tone on pricing, AUR improvement, and tariff mitigation was better than- feared amidst a backdrop of low investor expectations. However, this was offset by a longer- dated path to turnaround at

Athleta which is weighing on consolidated revenue growth and drove a surprising gross margin miss this quarter. While management is implementing change at this brand (including new leadership) this will remain a drag in the near- term. We remain constructive on GAP's assertion journey, but acknowledge the puts and takes in the quarter.

2Q result: GAP reported 2Q25 EPS of \(0.57, above GS/FactSet consensus estimates of\) 0.54/\(0.55. Consolidated comparable sales were up +1% Y/Y vs. GSe at +1.5%, and consolidated net sales came in line with GSe at +0.1%. Comps for each of GAP's brands were reported at +4.0% at Gap Global (vs. GS/consensus at 4.5%/3.5%), Old Navy at +2.0% (vs. GS/consensus at 2.0%/1.5%), Banana Republic at +4.0% (vs. GS/consensus at 0.5%), and Athleta at -9.0% (vs. GSe at -7.0%). By brand, Gap Global sales increased +0.8% Y/Y (vs. GSe at 4.8%), Old Navy sales grew +1.3% Y/Y (vs. GSe at 1.1%), Banana Republic global sales declined -0.8% Y/Y (vs. GSe at -6.0%), and Athleta sales decreased -11.2% Y/Y (vs. GSe of -7.8%). Gross margin of 41.2% was modestly below GS/consensus of 41.8%/41.9%, with management calling out \~150bps contraction in merchandise margin (due to cycling of last year's credit card benefit and pressure at the Athleta brand) and \~10bps ROD leverage. SG&A expense at 33.4% of sales was well- controlled vs. GS/consensus at 34.5%/34.4%, although benefited from a timing shift that will weigh on both 3Q and 4Q. Net, operating margin of 7.8% in the quarter was above GS/consensus expectations of 7.3%/7.5%.

Outlook: GAP updated its full year outlook which now includes impact from tariffs (as of August 7th rates). GAP still expects revenue growth of +1- 2%, which compares to GS/consensus at +1.9%/+1.6%. The company now expects operating margin of 6.7% to 7.0%, which now includes 100- 110bps of net tariff impact (vs. operating income growth of +8- 10% prior without tariffs incorporated), which compares to GS/consensus at 6.9%/7.1%. For 3Q, the company expects sales to grow in the range of +1.5% to +2.5% Y/Y (vs. GS/consensus at 3.1%/2.0%), gross margin deleverage of 150- 170bps including 200bps of net tariff impact (vs. GS/consensus at - 90bps/- 50bps), and slight operating expense deleverage (vs. GS/consensus at - 5.8%/- 6.6%).

We update our 2025/2026/2027 EPS estimates to \(2.09 / 2.19 / 2.19 / 2.51 from\) 2.09/2.17/2.55 prior to reflect the 2Q result and to update our tariff assumptions for management's latest guidance. We maintain our 12- month price target of \(26 on our updated estimates and as we roll forward our Q5- Q8 EV/EBITDA valuation methodology, with our target valuation multiple still at 5.25x.

Key downside risks include: (1) Long- term cost headwinds from freight and wage inflation driving margin pressure. (2) Prolonged pressure on the low- income consumer's spending power. (3) Weak execution. (4) Increased competition with off- price peers or other apparel businesses.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
